message.content:
The start symbol expands only in one way:

S → NT11 NT28  

NT11 produces exactly the single terminal t8.  
Therefore every sentence in the language begins with t8 and the rest of the string (here the last 20 tokens) must be generated by NT28.

NT28 has only four possibilities:

1. NT28 → 't7'        (1 token)
2. NT28 → 't0'        (1 token)
3. NT28 → 't2'        (1 token)
4. NT28 → NT34 NT37   (≥2 tokens)

Because 20 tokens remain, the only viable rule is NT28 → NT34 NT37, so the 20-token tail must split into a prefix produced by NT34 followed by a suffix produced by NT37.

Observe what NT37 can generate.

• It can be a single terminal: 't3', 't6', 't8', or 't9'.  
  – Our tail ends with t1, so a 1-token NT37 is impossible.

• Otherwise NT37 → NT23 NT22.  
  – NT23 must be 't9', 't5', or 't2'.  
  – NT22 ultimately ends with exactly one of 't8', 't0', or 't1' and any tokens before that are built only from
        't1', or 't2 t9', or 't2 t3'.

Hence every string of NT37 that is longer than one token has the form
   (t9|t5|t2)  followed by  [zero or more of  t1 | t2 t9 | t2 t3]  and finishing with  (t8|t0|t1).

Consequently the last two tokens of such a string must belong to {t8,t0,t1} with the very last token itself in that same set.

The given 20-token tail ends with “… t9  t8  t1”.  
The final token t1 satisfies the required ending, but the token immediately before it is t8, which is not permitted in the pre-ending position (only t1 or t2 are allowed there). Therefore no decomposition of the tail can match the pattern forced by NT37.

Because NT37 cannot produce the end of the string, the split NT34 NT37 is impossible, so NT28 cannot generate the 20-token tail.

Consequently S cannot derive the entire 21-token string.

No

From the start–symbol the only possible first step is  

S → NT11 NT28 with NT11 → 't8'.  
This fixes the first token of every sentence in the language to t8, which agrees with the given string.  
The rest of the string (18 tokens)

t4 t1 t2 t3 t1 t9 t7 t8 t5 t6 t5 t3 t1 t2 t9 t5 t6 t9  

must therefore be generated by NT28.

NT28, however, has only the following kinds of productions:

1. NT28 → 't7' | 't0' | 't2' (single-token strings)  
2. NT28 → NT34 NT37 (two non-terminals)

Because 18 > 1, rule (2) is mandatory, so the 18 tokens must be split into a prefix produced by NT34 and a suffix produced by NT37, with the very first token (t4) coming from NT34.

But NT34 can begin with t4 only in one way:

NT34 → NT5 NT16 and NT5 → 't4'  

(All other possibilities for NT34 yield first terminals t1 or t3, never t4.)  
Consequently the second token of the substring must be the first terminal produced by NT16.

Yet NT16 can start only with  

• 't5', 't6', or 't4' (if it uses its single-terminal rules), or  
• 't9' or 't3' (if it uses NT16 → NT31 NT26, since NT31 → 't9' | 't3').

Thus NT16 can never yield t1 as its first terminal.  
But the second token in the required substring is t1, yielding an immediate contradiction.

Hence no derivation for the remaining 18 tokens exists, so NT28—and therefore S—cannot generate the given string.

No
